    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What Purity Means for a Component"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "pure function"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is one that: (1) given the same inputs, always returns the same output, and (2) produces no observable side effects — it does not mutate anything outside its own scope. React requires component functions to be pure in exactly this sense."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For a React component, the inputs are "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "props"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "state"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "context"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". The output is JSX. A pure component must return the same JSX tree whenever it receives the same props, state, and context — regardless of how many times or in what order React calls it."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Purity is the foundational contract that allows React to batch renders, skip redundant renders with "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "code"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "React.memo"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": ", pause and resume renders in concurrent mode, and double-invoke renders in development (StrictMode) to catch accidental side effects."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Side-by-side diagram of a pure vs impure component and what each enables or breaks",
          "title": null
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pure vs Impure: The Core Distinction"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The key question to ask about any code inside a component body: does this code "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "read or write anything outside the component's own call frame"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "? If so, it is a side effect and makes the component impure."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "table",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "tableRow",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "tableHeader",
                "attrs": {
                  "colspan": 1,
                  "rowspan": 1,
                  "colwidth": null
                },
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "marks": [
                          {
                            "type": "bold"
                          }
                        ],
                        "text": "Allowed in render"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "tableHeader",
                "attrs": {
                  "colspan": 1,
                  "rowspan": 1,
                  "colwidth": null
                },
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "marks": [
                          {
                            "type": "bold"
                          }
                        ],
                        "text": "Not allowed in render"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
