      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// Pure — reads only props, creates local values, returns JSX\nfunction ProductCard({ name, price, discount }) {\n  const displayPrice = discount ? price * (1 - discount) : price;\n  const label = displayPrice < 10 ? 'Budget' : 'Standard';\n  return (\n    <div>\n      <h2>{name}</h2>\n      <p>{label}: ${displayPrice.toFixed(2)}</p>\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n\n// Impure — writes to external state during render\nlet totalRendered = 0; // module-level\nfunction ProductCard({ name, price }) {\n  totalRendered++; // SIDE EFFECT: mutates external variable\n  return <div>{name}</div>;\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why React Requires Purity"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The purity requirement is not aesthetic — it enables core React features:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Batching: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "When React batches multiple state updates into one render, it skips the intermediate renders. If render produced side effects, those effects would be silently skipped. Purity guarantees skipping is safe."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Concurrent rendering: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "React 18 can pause, discard, and restart renders. A paused render that produced side effects would leave external state in a half-applied state — a correctness disaster. Purity makes discarding safe."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "React.memo / useMemo: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "These optimizations skip re-rendering a component when its inputs haven't changed. If render was impure, the memoization might return stale output. Purity guarantees memoized output is correct."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "StrictMode double-invocation: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "In development, React calls each component twice to detect accidental side effects. Idempotent output (same result both times) means the component is pure. A changed result reveals impurity."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Server-side rendering: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "On the server, React calls component functions in a context where browser APIs do not exist. Pure components render correctly; impure ones crash or silently corrupt."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Impurity Patterns to Avoid"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pattern 1: Mutating a Module-Level Variable"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// BUG: module-level variable mutated during render\nlet counter = 0;\n\nfunction VisitCounter() {\n  counter++; // impure — mutates shared variable\n  return <p>Page visited {counter} times this session.</p>;\n}\n\n// In StrictMode: called twice → shows 2 on first mount instead of 1\n// In concurrent mode: partially-rendered trees may cause extra increments"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Fix: if you need to count something, use "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "useEffect"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (which runs after render) or "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "useState"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (which React owns and controls correctly)."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pattern 2: Writing to a Ref During Render"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// BUG: ref written during render\nfunction Timer() {\n  const renderTimeRef = useRef(null);\n  renderTimeRef.current = Date.now(); // impure — side effect in render\n  return <div>...</div>;\n}\n\n// Refs escape React's control — writing during render means\n// StrictMode double-invocation overwrites the first value, hiding the problem.\n\n// FIX: write to refs in effects\nfunction Timer() {\n  const renderTimeRef = useRef(null);\n  useEffect(() => {\n    renderTimeRef.current = Date.now(); // runs after commit — safe\n  });\n  return <div>...</div>;\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pattern 3: Mutating Props or State"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// BUG: mutating a prop object\nfunction SortedList({ items }) {\n  items.sort(); // MUTATION — props are not yours to change!\n  return <ul>{items.map(i => <li key={i}>{i}</li>)}</ul>;\n}\n\n// FIX: create a new sorted array\nfunction SortedList({ items }) {\n  const sorted = [...items].sort(); // copy first, then sort\n  return <ul>{sorted.map(i => <li key={i}>{i}</li>)}</ul>;\n}\n\n// BUG: mutating state directly\nfunction Counter() {\n  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);\n  count++; // WRONG — mutates the snapshot, does not trigger re-render\n  return <div>{count}</div>;\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pattern 4: Side Effects in the Component Body"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// BUG: starting a network request during render\nfunction UserProfile({ userId }) {\n  fetch(`/api/user/${userId}`).then(/* ... */); // side effect in render!\n  // This runs on every render, every StrictMode double-invoke\n  // → double requests, race conditions, infinite loops possible\n  return <div>Loading...</div>;\n}\n\n// FIX: move to useEffect\nfunction UserProfile({ userId }) {\n  const [user, setUser] = useState(null);\n  useEffect(() => {\n    let cancelled = false;\n    fetch(`/api/user/${userId}`)\n      .then(r => r.json())\n      .then(data => { if (!cancelled) setUser(data); });\n    return () => { cancelled = true; };\n  }, [userId]);\n  if (!user) return <div>Loading...</div>;\n  return <div>{user.name}</div>;\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Local Mutation Is Fine"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Purity does not forbid all mutation — only mutation of things that existed "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "before"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " the render call. Creating new objects and arrays inside the component and mutating them before returning is perfectly fine:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "function PlayerList({ players }) {\n  // Creating and building a local array — fine, no external mutation\n  const sorted = [];\n  for (const p of players) {\n    sorted.push({ ...p, rank: computeRank(p) });\n  }\n  sorted.sort((a, b) => b.score - a.score);\n\n  return (\n    <ol>\n      {sorted.map(p => (\n        <li key={p.id}>{p.rank}. {p.name} — {p.score}</li>\n      ))}\n    </ol>\n  );\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "sorted"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " array is created fresh on every render and is never shared outside the function. Mutating it is equivalent to building a local variable — it has no observable external effect."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Where Side Effects Do Belong"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "React provides two dedicated escape hatches for side effects:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "useEffect: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Runs asynchronously after the component renders and commits to the DOM. Use for data fetching, subscriptions, manually updating the DOM, logging, analytics."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "useLayoutEffect: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Runs synchronously after the DOM is updated but before the browser paints. Use for layout measurements that must happen before the user sees anything."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Event handlers: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Side effects triggered by user actions (click, submit, change) belong in event handlers, not in the component body."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "function AnalyticsPage({ pageId }) {\n  // WRONG: side effect during render\n  // analytics.track('page_view', { pageId }); // DON'T\n\n  // RIGHT: side effect in useEffect (runs after render)\n  useEffect(() => {\n    analytics.track('page_view', { pageId });\n  }, [pageId]);\n\n  // RIGHT: side effect in event handler\n  function handleDownload() {\n    analytics.track('download', { pageId }); // fine here\n    startDownload(pageId);\n  }\n\n  return <button onClick={handleDownload}>Download</button>;\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Detecting Impurity with StrictMode"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "React's "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "<StrictMode>"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " wrapper double-invokes component functions in development to surface impurity bugs:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// In main.jsx / index.jsx\nimport { StrictMode } from 'react';\nimport { createRoot } from 'react-dom/client';\n\ncreateRoot(document.getElementById('root')).render(\n  <StrictMode>\n    <App />\n  </StrictMode>\n);"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "With StrictMode active, every component function is called twice per render in development. If your component is pure, both calls produce the same JSX and React uses the second result. If they differ, you have an impurity — and React will reveal it."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// StrictMode exposes this bug:\nlet count = 0;\nfunction Buggy() {\n  count++; // first call: count=1, second call: count=2 — inconsistent!\n  return <div>{count}</div>;\n  // Without StrictMode you might see 1. With StrictMode you see 2.\n  // The discrepancy tells you render is impure.\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "StrictMode only double-invokes in "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "bold"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "development"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": ". Production runs are single-invocation. The double-invoke is intentional: it amplifies the signal of impurity so bugs surface during development, not in production."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Idempotency: The Practical Standard"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The precise requirement is not just purity in the mathematical sense but "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "idempotency"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ": calling the component function multiple times with the same inputs must produce the same JSX output each time. React guarantees it will call each component at least once per render — StrictMode guarantees at least twice. Your component must handle both."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// Idempotent — safe to call N times\nfunction UserBadge({ username, isPremium }) {\n  return (\n    <span className={isPremium ? 'badge-gold' : 'badge-basic'}>\n      {username}\n    </span>\n  );\n  // Call it 1 time or 100 times with the same props → same output\n}\n\n// Not idempotent — result changes on repeated calls\nlet id = 0;\nfunction UniqueItem({ label }) {\n  id++; // increments every call\n  return <div id={`item-${id}`}>{label}</div>;\n  // First call: id=\"item-1\", second call: id=\"item-2\" — NOT idempotent\n}\n\n// FIX: generate IDs outside render (or use useId hook)\nfunction UniqueItem({ label }) {\n  const id = useId(); // React-managed, stable across re-renders\n  return <div id={id}>{label}</div>;\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The useId Hook for Stable IDs"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A common impurity is generating unique IDs during render using "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Math.random()"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " or incrementing counters. React provides "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "useId"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " as the pure alternative:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import { useId } from 'react';\n\nfunction LabeledInput({ label, type = 'text' }) {\n  const id = useId(); // stable across renders and SSR-hydration-safe\n\n  return (\n    <div>\n      <label htmlFor={id}>{label}</label>\n      <input id={id} type={type} />\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n\n// Multiple instances each get their own stable, unique ID\n// <LabeledInput label=\"Name\" />   → id=\":r0:\"\n// <LabeledInput label=\"Email\" />  → id=\":r1:\"\n// Same IDs on server and client — no hydration mismatch"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Purity and Performance Optimizations"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pure components unlock React's memoization APIs. Without purity, these APIs would return stale results:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// React.memo skips re-render when props haven't changed\n// This is only safe if the component is pure\nconst ExpensiveChart = React.memo(function Chart({ data, color }) {\n  const points = computePoints(data); // expensive computation\n  return <canvas data-points={points} style={{ color }} />;\n});\n\n// useMemo caches a computed value across renders\nfunction Dashboard({ rawData, filters }) {\n  // Only recomputes when rawData or filters change\n  const processed = useMemo(\n    () => processData(rawData, filters),\n    [rawData, filters]\n  );\n  return <Table rows={processed} />;\n}\n\n// useCallback caches a function reference\nfunction Parent({ onEvent }) {\n  const handleClick = useCallback(() => {\n    onEvent('clicked');\n  }, [onEvent]); // stable reference when onEvent doesn't change\n  return <PureChild onClick={handleClick} />;\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "All three APIs rely on React being able to skip work. They are only correct if the skipped work would produce the same output — which is only guaranteed for pure components."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Rendering on the Server"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In SSR (server-side rendering), React calls component functions in a Node.js environment where browser APIs like "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "window"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "document"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "localStorage"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " do not exist. Impure components that access browser globals crash on the server:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// BUG: accesses browser API during render\nfunction ThemeProvider({ children }) {\n  const theme = localStorage.getItem('theme'); // crashes on server!\n  return <ThemeContext.Provider value={theme}>{children}</ThemeContext.Provider>;\n}\n\n// FIX: read browser state in useEffect (runs client-only)\nfunction ThemeProvider({ children }) {\n  const [theme, setTheme] = useState('light'); // safe default for SSR\n\n  useEffect(() => {\n    // Runs only in the browser, after hydration\n    const saved = localStorage.getItem('theme');\n    if (saved) setTheme(saved);\n  }, []);\n\n  return <ThemeContext.Provider value={theme}>{children}</ThemeContext.Provider>;\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Summary"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A pure component is one that returns the same JSX for the same props, state, and context, with no observable side effects. Purity enables React to batch updates, skip redundant renders, restart paused renders, and run correctly on the server. The golden rule: render must be a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "read-only snapshot"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " of your inputs. All writes go into effects or event handlers. StrictMode's double-invocation is your CI check for purity — a component that passes StrictMode in development is almost certainly pure."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Key takeaways: "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Same inputs must always produce same JSX. No mutation of external variables, props, or state during render. Local mutation of freshly-created objects is fine. Side effects go in useEffect or event handlers. StrictMode double-invokes to surface impurity. Purity unlocks React.memo, useMemo, concurrent rendering, and SSR correctness."
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
